26 2021-01-04 nightmare Nausea; Vomiting; Diarrhea; Bad dreams; Extreme chills; Heavy amount of sweating; This is a spontane... Read more
Close
Nausea; Vomiting; Diarrhea; Bad dreams; Extreme chills; Heavy amount of sweating; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable other HCP (patient). A 26-year-old male patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (lot number: EK5730), via an unspecified route of administration in left arm, on 24Dec2020 09:30 AM at single dose for COVID-19 immunization. Facility where the most recent COVID-19 vaccine was administered was workplace clinic. The patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19 prior to vaccination. Since the vaccination, the patient was not tested for COVID-19. Allergies to medications, food, or other products included Bactrim. Relevant medical history included Kyphosis, Binge Eating Disorder, Anxiety, Depression, ADHD, Obesity, Hypertension, all ongoing. No other vaccines were received within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. The medications received within 2 weeks of vaccination included omeprazole(PROTONIX), Lisinopril, HCTZ, Atenolol, vilazodone hydrochloride(VIIBRYD). The patient experienced Nausea, Vomiting, Diarrhea, Bad dreams, Extreme chills, Heavy amount of sweating, Elevated motivation to work/be productive, Very optimistic on 28Dec2020 01:00 PM. No treatment was received for the events. The outcome of the events was not recovered.

Close
First dose (12/30/20): Vivid dreams and frequent nocturnal awakenings upon receiving the first dose. Experienced tiredness the next day, unsure of whether it was the vaccine or lack of sleep. Second dose (1/19/21): Awakened every hour to1.5 hours that night with markedly vivid dreams in between awakenings. Upon trying to take a nap, the same situation occurred, with a vivid dream and awakening within 1.5 hours. I have had vivid dreams in the past, but not with that frequency before. The dreams and difficulty sleeping improved the next night and had resolved within 24 hours.

Subjective fever (axillary temp 98.2F), chills, generalized weakness, malaise, headache, brain fog. Onset 3AM, resolved by 10PM with PO Tylenol 500mg plus PO ibuprofen 800mg taken together, as well as warm soup/tea and a nap.

Close
After receiving the first dose of the COVID vaccine I was experiencing headaches, dizziness, lightheadedness, palpitations, and nausea. The first dose was on 12/21/20. These symptoms resolved around 12/26/20. I received the second dose of the COVID vaccine on 01/11/21. I began experiencing symptoms on 01/12/21. The symptoms I was experiencing were lightheadedness, dizziness, and brain fog/confusion. These symptoms got significantly worse from 01/13/21 - 01/24/21 and I began developing profound confusion/brain fog, diplopia, blurry vision, headaches, feeling like I'm swaying on a boat, and the "feeling of being drunk". As of 01/25/21, the symptoms have seemed to get better and I am starting to feel more like myself. The drunk feeling and mild blurry vision are still present as of today 01/28/21.

1/28 - First dose of vaccine received. Arm felt heavy, not sore. Throughout the day, fatigue gradually increased. Before bed time, had cold sweats and shakes. 1/29 - woke up feeling perfectly fine. 2/17 - Second dose of vaccine. Arm felt sore and was sore two days after. From 2/18-2/20, I noticed the effects of the Cymbalta were gradually decreasing and was experiencing side effects (shocks from toe to head every step). Turns out that even with taking my regular dose of the Cymbalta, my body after 2 hours feels like I had never taken it. 2/20 - After experiencing heavy shocks, shaking, and heart racing, I went home after coming into work 3 hours later. 2/21 - Woke up today feeling dizzy, fatigued, and weak. I know that operating a motor vehicle will not be possible for me.
26 2021-03-04 feeling abnormal I took notes during my wait time: -6 minutes in my throat felt weird, but different than normal alle... Read more
Close
I took notes during my wait time: -6 minutes in my throat felt weird, but different than normal allergic reactions to foods. I prepared my Epi-Pen so I have easier access at this time. -9 minutes in the sides of my tongue were slightly itchy. -11 minutes in and I felt as though the saliva in the back of my throat was thicker and I needed to clear my throat a bit more often, similar to allergic reactions. -15 minutes in, I felt my heart pound once out of beat, but my heart rhythm returned to normal immediately. Tongue itchiness also became intermittent rather than constant. -18 minutes in, overall condition improved and I felt better. -22 minutes in, my throat felt scratchy like I would if I consumed legumes (chickpeas, green peas, soy beans, etc.) but also oddly warm, which was out of the norm. No treatments needed given mild reactions. I went to work, but notified my co-workers of my reaction, so if my condition worsens they can help administer my Epi-Pen. I am reporting this at 9:21 am on 03/05/2021, roughly an hour after my first dose.

26 2021-03-15 loss of personal independence in daily activities, impaired work ability On 2/13/2021, I began to experience both enhanced and new musculoskeletal and neurological symptoms ... Read more
Close
On 2/13/2021, I began to experience both enhanced and new musculoskeletal and neurological symptoms that have not completely resolved still, today, 3/16/2021. While I had experienced some slight discomfort and pain of the b/l thumbs 2-3 weeks prior to 2/13, I began to experience increased pain up to the forearm in both arms on that day. In addition to pain, I had large muscular knots in the superior forearms, especially the right arm. The lower right arm felt extremely tight, and I was having difficulty raising the arm and gripping things. This continued for 2-3 weeks on the right arm. During that time, symptoms worsened on the left arm, while improving on the right arm. A week after the initial symptoms my left arm became worse, and I was struggling to lift objects as light as a sheet of paper. I was also having trouble typing at work, dialing the phone, and opening or closing my hand. Just over a week after symptoms began, I left work to determine a cause and solution for my issues. I also began to have tremors, extreme muscle spasms, and involuntary movements around this time for about 2-3 weeks. While the neurological symptoms have mostly subsided, still, today, 3/16/2021, I continue to deal with various inflammatory musculoskeletal symptoms affecting mostly my left arm, but also my right arm. Since yesterday, my left shoulder has begun to have pain as well, making raising my arm and reaching to the opposite side difficult due to pain. I have also had persistent popping of various joints in both arms since the initial symptoms began.

27 2021-04-30 feeling abnormal 27 year old male with Down's Syndrome and no other past medical history received second COVID-19 vac... Read more
Close
27 year old male with Down's Syndrome and no other past medical history received second COVID-19 vaccine on 4/27/2021. On 4/30/2021 began "feeling poorly" with nausea/vomiting and possible chest discomfort. Originally presented to ED on morning of 4/30 - EKG completed demonstrated diffused ST elevation. Patient was transferred to Medical Center for heart catheterization. Left heart catheterization demonstrated normal coronary arteries and LVEDP of 25. Stat ECHO demonstrated pericardial effusion and concern raised for myopericarditis. Patient subsequently transferred to a different Medical Center for higher level of care. Upon arrival to Medical Center plan was to intubate and take to cath lab for heart biopsy and PA catheter placement. However, upon intubation patient began to decompensate and subsequently developed cardiac arrest. During ACLS, VA ECMO was placed and therapeutic hypothermia was initiated. Following VA ECMO placement patient received IVIG, high dose methylprednisolone (1000 mg), anakinra 100 mg, and broad spectrum antibiotics (vancomycin and Zosyn). Despite these efforts the patient continued to have hemodynamic instability and was on high dose vasopressors (epinephrine, norepinephrine, dopamine, angiotensin II, vasopressin). Patient subsequently suffered another cardiac arrest, briefly regained pulse with high dose vasopressors, but subsequently lost pulse despite best efforts and died on 5/1/2021 at approximately 13:00.

After about an hour following my second COVID-19 Injection I began feeling warm. My forehead felt warmer so I figure I may have had a slight fever at that point. I received a metallic (Note I say metallic but I know it wasn't actually metal but that's simply the best way I can describe the taste I experienced) following the injection about 5 minutes after. My arm remained sore following and still remains sore as of this report. I experienced a decline in mental acuity following about an hour after injection. I began to feel lightheaded and exhausted to the point I was experiencing severe disorientation and confusion. I was having trouble putting sentences together and experienced a ringing sensation in the ears. I felt like I wasn't even present anymore. I couldn't comprehend things around me and apparently had conversations I don't even remember having. Note that at that point I had gotten home but don't even remember getting home. I just know that this did not begin to wear off until around 8:45pm when it was like someone flipped a switch and I suddenly was coherent again. It was an odd sensation to experience. The arm remained sore and the metallic taste returned briefly after this experience. I experienced a similar feeling from the HPV injection years ago, but just like this it was a temporary thing that resulted in no long term issues. However, I cannot tell you fully what we did the rest of the day until around 845-9 pm. I also remember becoming partly agitated after the injection like my body just all of a sudden took notice of something and shot into action. I had received my allergy injections this same day about two hours earlier as well and none of these reactions ever occur with those for me. I continued to drink liquid as far as I know as there were a few empty bottles of water next to me. I have no recollection of getting them. It's odd. There's just this brief moment in time that is just missing from my memory with a few short bits and pieces that are there like a puzzle with some missing pieces. I feel I became so fatigued I could not function. My emotions I remember were off and hard to control during this period too. I felt like I was having some random mood swings. I feel ok now though aside from the upset stomach occasionally and the fatigue and arm pain (but even the arm pain has partly decreased now). It all ceased. I have a number of health issues outside of this but have not experienced this long of a period of almost intermittent amnesia and incoherency following an injection before. I believe it made me that much more tired or reacted with one of my many conditions or genetic variants that perhaps may have been part of this. I'm happy to provide anything I can to help with this. I am greatly appreciative of all the CDC has done to get us this vaccine and continues to do to ensure our safety both before and after injection. It is commendable. I did fill out my survey through the V-Safe portal as well and will continue to follow up there should I have any changes. I have not sought medical care following this event as the coherency and such have seemed to resolve in regards to the vaccine injection. Only thing left are known side effects at this point besides an occasional increase in numbness and tingling that I already experience in my legs and feet. My absolute best guess for the cause is my immune system which already has some issues regulating (doesn't always like to learn everything it should and we are currently searching for an undiagnosed autoimmune disorder currently going on as well in me) on top of allergy shots today. it was perhaps just a bit too much demand on it all at once. But it seems to be balancing out again now.

He stated his heart is so weak, that he cannot work right now, but the structure of his heart is fine and has not had any damage. The hospital staff thought that maybe the patient had a chronic heart issue that he just did not know about, and that the stress of this event maybe made it kick into overdrive, but he states that the cardiologist said that was not the case, because the structure of his heart is fine, and the only thing they can see is that the heart is pumping weak. One physician even suggested that due to the shock of the event, he might have Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy, which is a broken heart, but because the structure of his heart is okay, it should be reversible. He stated that he is hoping he will heal up good, because he is young and has no pre-existing conditions. He added that his heart is in such a state right now; he has to wear an external defibrillator. The patient stated that all these happened about 20 minutes after he received the vaccine, and he was admitted to the hospital from 21Dec2020 to 25Dec2020. His neurological symptoms have resolved except that he has a stutter that he did not have before and his mouth is fatigued easily, so he has to slow down when he is eating, but now he can eat regular for the most part. The patient confirmed that he was not specifically prescribed the product; it was administered to him at his place of work, but it was optional. He stated he considered how he is working with COVID patients every day, and given the circumstance, he thought that it would be a best practice for him to get the vaccine. He had not gone to his primary care doctor in a while because he had been fine and healthy, but he called them and found out that his primary care had retired, so he has to find a new one now. Regarding the issues finding words and trouble speaking, he stated that he has improved, but it is still ongoing, he is just stuck in a plateau zone. With the Ventricular Tachycardia, he stated that this is an ongoing issue, as he has to wear the life vest even though he has no need to activate it yet. He did have one minor bought of the VTach, but because he is a therapist, he knows how to take care of it with relaxation techniques, he knows how to manage it. He had one bought of VTach the evening prior, but he was able to get it under control. The doctors have him on medication to help keep his heart rate at bay. He has never had to use medication before and is on the following medications to help keep his heart rate at bay: Metoprolol 25mg one tablet once daily by mouth and Lisinopril 5mg one tablet once daily by mouth. The VTach has improved, it was good enough he was able to discharge home, but it is still a concern. His cardiologist said that, basically his hope, is that once his body recover from the whole shock of everything, then his ejection fraction will heal, and his heart will heal. He again stated that the doctor told him that the structure of his heart is perfectly fine; he has thick walls in his heart, no leaking valves, and the heart was not conducting any abnormal signals. The doctor just said that right now, his heart is super weak and that it is an acute problem. With the Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy, he states that two doctors mentioned this diagnosis, but he confirmed that he was not actually diagnosed with this issue, he was just diagnosed with Ventricular Tachycardia. The outcome of the ejection fraction down to 25% was unknown to the patient at this time as he has not had another EKG or echocardiogram, but the cardiologist told him that the cardiologist expects that this will not be resolved quickly anyway. The patient confirmed that he did not receive any other vaccines on the same day he received the COVID vaccine. The only other vaccine he had this year was the flu vaccine which he got back in Oct2020. He does not have this pulled up at this time, but he does have access to this stuff and can provide it later, if requested. He is curious about the next steps from here to how his case is processed. He is also curious if this information would help Pfizer make modifications to the vaccine if it is found that a lot of people are having the same reaction as he did. He is also wondering, given his situation, that probably he is not going to get the second dose, for his safety, but he is wondering what percentage of effectiveness the first dose does having just covered. 31 2021-05-25 sleep disorder Upon receiving the second dose of the COVID-19 vaccine, I immediately felt tingling or chills in the... Read more
Close
Upon receiving the second dose of the COVID-19 vaccine, I immediately felt tingling or chills in the arm where the shot was administered. This developed into muscle soreness as I sat through the waiting period before leaving the facility. (For this reason, I had taken acetaminophen at about 8:30 that morning.) I experienced both of these symptoms after my first shot of this COVID-19 vaccine, so these did not concern me. After taking a nap back at my house, I woke up about 3:30 p.m. experiencing some partial numbness in my left arm, which received the injection. It was not inhibitive, but I can somewhat relate it to the neuropathy my mother experienced before being diagnosed with diabetes in 2005. It was a bit like the tingling I first experienced after the injection, but throughout the injected arm. As I continued through that afternoon and evening, my arm kept getting stiffer and stiffer. This prompted me to take my temperature at about 8 p.m. and then again at 10 p.m. Both of these tests resulted in a normal temperature of 98.3 or 98.4 degrees. By the time I was about to climb into bed at midnight, the stiffness had spread to my shoulder joint -- such that almost any movement of that arm elicited some mild discomfort, especially if I leaned against the wall with that shoulder or raised my arm above my head. I took a third dose of acetaminophen. My normal prone sleeping position was not comfortable with this stiffness, so I did my best to sleep on my back. Next, I woke up too hot about 3:30 a.m. (Wednesday, May 26) and could not get back to sleep. Full-body chills set in soon after, prompting me to turn off my ceiling fan. I faced some mild nausea as I attempted to get comfortable in bed again. I suspected I was feverish by at least 4 a.m., but I did not get up to check my temperature until 5 a.m. The thermometer gave a reading of 100.3 degrees, so I took another dose of acetaminophen (my fourth in 24 hours) and tried to go back to sleep.

The reason I felt it so important to submit this report is because I had never heard of anyone experiencing side-effects that severe. Of course I had heard it could wipe you out, give you chills, aches, and exhaustion - but I had never heard that it could lead to a seizure so scary that my best friend thought I might be dying. I absolutely do NOT want to discourage anyone from getting the vaccine, but I wish I had some notion that something so severe could happen to me.

34 2021-05-24 confusional state, feeling abnormal As a clinical monitor, I was called over to assess a driver slumped over in his seat. He had just re... Read more
Close
As a clinical monitor, I was called over to assess a driver slumped over in his seat. He had just received the second dose of the Pfizer vaccine approximately 10 minutes earlier. The passenger (his fiance) said he was acting normal until she heard him grunt and then realized that he was passed out. While attempting to lay flat, I performed a jaw thrust that yielded a stridulous inspiration but was still unresponsive. He did not have a palpable carotid pulse. Paramedics was summoned emergently. Within 30-45 seconds, he awoke but was confused and amnestic to the event. He had no physical complaints and no significant medical or allergy history. I auscultated his larynx (no stridor) and his lungs (CTA). His initial vitals: BP 90/51 HR 61 VR 16 SaO2 100% An electrocardiogram demonstrated a sinus rhythm without ischemic changes or evidence of conduction delay. His glucose was 119. Over the next 30 minutes, he was able to drink two bottles of water and some orange juice. That said, he still said he "felt off." Repeat vital signs: BP 118/62 HR 69 SaO2 100%. The medics advised him to follow up with his doctor, preferably today. His fiance agreed to drive him to an ED near their home for a more thorough evaluation. I provided her my phone number to provide to the ED for any questions. His clinical syndrome was consistent with a syncopal episode associated with orthostatic hypotension. Low suspicion for anaphylaxis.

Nothing - EKG was again normal and lab work was normal. The doctor told me it's all in my head - anxiety. However, I'm not anxious and I'm a very level headed individual. It's now day 12 and I feel overall awful. I can't concentrate on anything. I'm not thinking clearly and forgetting simple things. The dull feeling and electric shocks on my left side continue. I've never felt this bad before. I'm a healthy 34 year old that exercises regularly, has never smoked or done drugs, rarely drinks alcohol, and eats generally very healthy. If given a second chance I would not take the covid shot. I am praying this goes away.

About 34 hours after the shot, I woke up around 2:00 am with intense abdominal and back pain, a fever, and vomiting. I took Tylenol and tried to rest, but my discomfort continued throughout the day. By the afternoon of March 30, I began to worry that I was having more than a typical vaccine reaction. The PA who saw me assessed my symptoms, performed an abdominal exam, and then dismissed my issues as a bad vaccine reaction. He gave me an injection of toradol and sent me home. My symptoms subsided after the toradol injection, but I still felt unwell. On March 31, I had a previously scheduled visit with my primary care doctor. During the visit, I described my symptoms after receiving the vaccine, but I was told again that I was just having a really bad reaction to the vaccine. Throughout that day, my condition continued to worsen, and by the evening of the 31st I developed a fever and my abdominal pain returned. I scheduled an emergency telemedicine visit. I described my symptoms and described the pain I was feeling, but again, I was told I was having a bad vaccine reaction. On the morning of April 1, I woke up with a fever and debilitating abdominal pain. I drove myself to the ER where I was diagnosed appendicitis. My appendix was about to rupture, so I was rushed into surgery. I was released after several days but had to return.

Prescribed blood thinner Pradaxa for 3 months with no known cause of clots that caused this Pulmonary Embolism. Kidney test and Heart appeared normal. Still waiting on genetic testing. Lung infract has caused lasting chest pain and my breathing has yet to return back to normal.

I had pain at the injection site the evening of receiving the injection, which still continues, though not too bad. Walking up today at around 7 am, I felt headache, achy all over, weakness, and some fever. I decided to stay home. I lay in bed most of the day, sometimes sleeping, sometimes watching YouTube videos on my phone. I was feeling kind of cold, so I snuggled completely under the covers, head and all. I got sweaty and had to uncover my head. I changed clothes. I got up a couple of times to urinate. Once, I felt some weakness, and had to support myself with my hand on the edge of the bathroom counter. Then, this afternoon, my headache was a bit worse. I got up to hop top the bathroom. I was urinating standing up, when I started feeling weak, so I supported myself with my hand, but almost immediately, I started feeling like I was going to fall, to faint, and to vomit. I hurriedly sat down on the toilet. I was still feeling nauseated and weak, so I learned back to take pressure off my abdomen, which was feeling slightly bloated. The bathroom fan was on, so it felt rather cold, but I started getting hotter and hotter, sweating profusely. At the same time, I just sat there trying to recover, and started feeling pins and needles in my forearms, but not like they had fallen asleep, just like someone were pressing down on my arms with blunt needles. I thought I was going to have to crawl back to bed. After a while, I started cooling off and feeling a little better. I went back to my room and changed clothes. I'm feeling warm and a bit weak and achy again, but nothing like that. I had only drunk 3 cups of water today, though I drank about 7 yesterday.

Patient denies any previous adverse reactions from vaccines.

he may pass out; feeling cold; chills; high heart rate; headache; palpitations; dizziness; Sweating; like a panic attack; got more anxious and scared; This is a spontaneous report from a Pfizer Sponsored Program. A 39-years-old male patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), via an unspecified route of administration on 25Apr2021 12:30 (Batch/Lot number was not reported) as 1ST DOSE, SINGLE for covid-19 immunisation (Age at vaccination: 39 years). The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. The patient states he took the shot at 12:30PM and came out of the technician's room, sat on the chair, and at that time, a minute after, the first thing he developed was dizziness, he started with dizziness, followed by palpitations and sweating and chilling, then headache and then he started a little bit of panic, like a panic attack, a lot of people gathered around him, he was scared because of it, and then the technician came out and mentioned he needed to go to the ER as soon as possible or he may pass out, he is unsure what she meant, but it scared him more (all on 25Apr2021). At the time he took the vaccine, 3 days before the vaccine came, his father, who is not in the US, but back home, his father was tested positive for corona, was in ICU at the time of caller's vaccine, so caller was stressed for 3-4 days before the vaccine, but at that time didn't feel like complete anxiety like when he took the vaccine, he was fine, not scared, but was 100% fine, not scared, then took the shot, started symptoms, got more anxious and scared and when people gathered, sometimes he felt totally stressed out because of his father. At the same time, if you are anxious and scared your heart beat can be high but not that high, his heart beat was 164 the other day, not the same, day, but after 24 hours. 25th was when he had the shot, 26Apr2021, at 1PM he was talking to someone on the phone, felt chills and right away his heart beat went from 120-140, he took water and sat down, walked a couple steps and picked up his oximeter and checked his oxygen and his heart rate was 120 to 130 to 140 then 160, and he sat down, took water and relaxed, it dropped down to 120, was 120-130 some time for 15-20 minutes then 911 guys came, took him to the hospital, and by the time he was at the hospital he was in the 100s. Feeling cold and chilling outcome: He was feeling cold chills, is now pretty much normal, sometimes he feels chills because he is in a T-shirt, he was fine going into the room taking the vaccine, when he came out, the first symptoms he started feeling was dizziness and feeling like falling down. High heart rate: was only those instances for 2 days, on the 25th and 26th for a little time, 15-20 minutes each day, after that he went to the cardiologist, who put a heart rate meter on his chest and observed his rate for 24 hours, and beat, and took a heart ultrasound and bloodwork and all his blood is fine and his heart rate is fine, after that he visited 3 times the cardiologist, who said his beat was fine and function was fine, and he was healthy and his physician after checking the report, she said the blood reports pretty much were normal. All the events occurred on 25Apr2021 and patient had an emergency room visit for all of the events and had a physician office visit for the event high heart rate. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included blood work: normal, heart rate: normal, heart rate: 100-160 and heart ultrasound scan: normal on an unspecified date. Outcome of the event Depressed level of consciousness was recovered on an unspecified date while outcome of the event heart rate increased was recovered on 26Apr2021. Outcome of the events panic attack and anxious mood was recovered on an unspecified date in 2021. Outcome of the remaining events was recovered on Apr2021. Information on the lot/batch number has been requested.
39 2021-06-03 nervousness 39 y/o with past medical history of Hypertension that presents with feeling weak, nervous and concer... Read more
Close
39 y/o with past medical history of Hypertension that presents with feeling weak, nervous and concerned for BP post vaccination. Patient states that this is the first vaccination in the two-dose series. Patient denies previous vaccination reaction. Patient states that the vaccination was received in the left arm. Patient placed in wheelchair and taken to the partitioned area with the NP and Paramedics. Patient initial vitals all within normal limits, 125/92 BP, 97 HR, 98 %RA, 12 Resp. Patient provided a bottle of water and monitored for 15 mins. Patient states that is feeling better and that feels that it was just nervousness. Patient vitals reassessed and normal, 127/85 BP, 98 HR, 99% RA, 12 Resp. Patient discharged in stable condition, ambulated without difficulty. NP encouraged patient to hydrate well since patient will be going back to work in an outdoor environment.
